<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<entry xmlns:functx="http://www.functx.com" xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xml:id="entry_ændax"
    xml:lang="os">
    <form type="lemma"><orth>ændax</orth></form>
    <sense><cit type="translation" xml:lang="ru">
            <q>нитка</q>
        </cit><cit type="translation" xml:lang="en">
            <q>thread</q>
        </cit></sense>
    <cit type="exampleGroup">
        <cit type="example">
            <quote>sūʒīn æmæ mуn saw ændax avær</quote>
            <cit type="translation" xml:lang="ru">
                <q>дай мне иглу и черные нитки</q>
            </cit>
            <cit type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                <q>give me a niddle and black threads</q>
            </cit>
        </cit>
    </cit>
    <cit type="exampleGroup">
        <cit type="example">
            <quote>sūʒīn æmæ mуn saw ændax avær</quote>
            <cit type="translation" xml:lang="ru">
                <q>дай мне иглу и черные нитки</q>
            </cit>
            <cit type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                <q>give me a niddle and black threads</q>
            </cit>
        </cit>
    </cit>
    <etym xml:lang="ru">Восходит к <mentioned xml:lang="ira"><lang/><w>*ham-tāka-</w></mentioned>.
        На иранской почве сюда же относится, вероятно, <mentioned xml:lang="fa"
                    ><lang/><w>tāya</w><gloss><q>тонкая нить</q></gloss></mentioned> (закономерно из
        %i*tāka%i → %itāga-%i, см.: <bibl><author>Horn</author><ref target="#ref_GIPh."
                /><biblScope>Abt. II, стр. 46)</biblScope></bibl>. Рефлексы <mentioned
            xml:lang="ira"><lang/><w>*ham-taka-</w></mentioned> находим в некоторых языках в
        значении ˈрабˈ (в смысле „связанный“, ср. по семантике <mentioned xml:lang="peo"
                ><lang/><w>bandaka-</w></mentioned>): <mentioned xml:lang="wbl"
            ><lang/><w>andag</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="srh"
                    ><lang/><w>indīj</w><gloss><q>раб</q></gloss></mentioned> (<bibl><ref
                target="#ref_Morgenstierne._IIFL"/><biblScope>II 514</biblScope></bibl>), в
        документах <mentioned xml:lang="pgd"><lang/><w>amtag’i</w></mentioned>
                (<bibl><author>Burrow,</author><ref target="#ref_BSOS"/><biblScope>VII
                779</biblScope></bibl>). Ср. <ref type="xr" target="#entry_tag"/> ˈнитьˈ, <ref
            type="xr" target="#entry_kættag"/>ˈполотноˈ, <ref type="xr" target="#entry_zældag"/>
        ˈшелкˈ и <ref type="xr" target="#entry_taxun"/> ’наряжатьˈ.%n<bibl><ref target="#ref_ОЯФ_I"
                /><biblScope>54</biblScope></bibl>.</etym>
    <etym xml:lang="en">Comes from <mentioned xml:lang="ira"><lang/><w>*ham-tāka-</w></mentioned>.
        Probably, <mentioned xml:lang="fa"><lang/><w>tāya</w><gloss><q>a thin
            thread</q></gloss></mentioned> (regulary from *tāka-→tāga-, см.:
                <bibl><author>Horn,</author><ref target="#ref_GIPh."/><biblScope>Abt. II
                46)</biblScope></bibl> has the same Iranian ethymology. Reflections of <mentioned
            xml:lang="ira"><lang/><w>*ham-taka-</w></mentioned> are also found in some languages
        with the meaning ˈslaveˈ (in the sense of ˈtied upˈ, cf. by semantics <mentioned
            xml:lang="peo"><lang/><w>bandaka-</w></mentioned>): <mentioned xml:lang="wbl"
                ><lang/><w>andag</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="srh"
                    ><lang/><w>indīj</w><gloss><q>slave</q></gloss></mentioned> (<bibl><ref
                target="#ref_Morgenstierne._IIFL"/><biblScope>II 514</biblScope></bibl>), in the
        documents кхарошти amtag’i (<bibl><author>Burrow</author><ref target="#ref_BSOS"
                /><biblScope>VII 779</biblScope></bibl>). Cf. <ref type="xr" target="#entry_tag"/>
        ˈthreadˈ, <ref type="xr" target="#entry_kættag"/> ˈlinenˈ, <ref type="xr"
            target="#entry_zældag"/> ˈsilkˈ and <ref type="xr" target="#entry_taxun"/> ˈto dress
                upˈ.%n<bibl><ref target="#ref_ОЯФ_I"/><biblScope>54</biblScope></bibl></etym>
</entry>
